points.title: Your account could be cancelled without notice

tosdr.tldr: Skype retains the right to cancel or limit your account at any time without notice to you in certain circumstances such as your failure to comply with terms of service, an extended period of inactivity, to comply with law enforcement or even for technical reasons. This could include deletion of your content or other information associated with or contained within your account.

topics.name: Right to leave the service
topics.subtitle: To avoid lock-in and stay in control
topics.title: Right to leave the service

tosdr.tldr: Skype generally retains instant, voice and video messages between 30 and 90 days. However they have the flexibility to keep your data for an undetermined amount of time if they need it to comply with legal requests. Their perpetual license terms mean they have a right to use your data even after you delete your account.

topics.subtitle: Your relationship with the service and the community
topics.title: Governance

tosdr.tldr: You are allowed to link to Skype sites on websites you own (for example your blog) but you will breach the terms of use and risk your account being terminated if content on that site damages Skype's reputation. This could infringe on the ability to write a bad review for example without risking your account.

topics.subtitle: How do services deal with government requests?
topics.title: Law and government requests

tosdr.tldr: This service informs users when their data is sought by the government, unless prohibited by law. With this knowledge, you have an opportunity to involve yourself if you think the request is unreasonable. This is covered by the Microsoft terms for all their free consumer services and applies to Skype users. Skype requests are included in Microsoft's transparency reports.

topics.name: Waiving your right
topics.subtitle: What kind of rights do you give up on?
topics.title: Waiving your right

tosdr.tldr: Terms include a binding arbitration clause and class action waiver that affects how disputes with Skype will be resolved in the USA. This clause is shared with Microsoft under their terms of service and is common to their many associated companies such as Hotmail, Bing, MSN etc. Microsoft  purchased Skype in 2011. This expressly applies for USA users and although the clause has been removed from the terms for non-USA users, references to it still exist.

topics.subtitle: Are users notified when terms change? Are they given enough time to find out what changed and discuss this with each other before deciding whether to continue to use the service under the new terms?

points.title: Broad copyright on your content and data

topics.description: Copyright law gives you control over how your content (texts, photos, videos, etc.) can be used, by whom they can be distributed, modified, etc. Sometimes, online services need your permission to perform certain tasks with your content. That's why they ask you to grant them a copyright license. But sometimes, the copyright license is so broad, that your content can be exploited by others without asking you.

topics.name: Scope of the copyright license
topics.subtitle: Do you grant only the necessary rights?
topics.title: Scope of the copyright license

tosdr.tldr: The licence you grant Skype when you accept their terms is very broad and covers your personal information and meta data. Terms suggest the licence does not apply to your content yet their privacy policy reserves the right to access, disclose and preserve personal data, including private content (instant messages, voicemails, stored messages or file transfers) at their discretion.

topics.name: Cookies
topics.subtitle: and related technologies
topics.title: Cookies

tosdr.tldr: Skype use cookies on your computer. This gives Skype various forms of information about you, your preferences and behaviour. You can choose to reject all cookies in your browser but this may prevent the service from working optimally. To track you on other Microsoft owned sites (Microsoft owns Skype) and across the web, Skype may also use web beacons and other technologies that act in a similar way to cookies and gather and contain information about your web browsing behaviour.

tosdr.tldr: If you send your friend an invitation to try Skype, you are consenting on your friend's behalf that you can supply their personal details (like an email address) to Skype.
